WHEREAS, in this capacity, he has spearheaded initiatives that provide formerly
incarcerated individuals with job training, housing support, and mentorship; his leadership has
directly impacted families, reduced recidivism, and strengthened communities by fostering
pathways to stability and success, and his work has given thousands of returning citizens not
only a second chance but a renewed sense of hope and purpose; and
WHEREAS, prior to serving as director of the Tennessee Office of Reentry, Dr. Arnold
was on the transition team of Shelby County District Attorney Steve Mulroy and chaired the
subcommittee that established the Shelby County Justice Review Unit, the second such unit in
the State of Tennessee focused on criminal justice reform and accountability; and
WHEREAS, his previous posts further include serving as director of Division Access,
Diversity, and Equity for the Tennessee Board of Regents and director of Academic Programs
and Interagency Grants for the Tennessee Higher Education Commission; and
WHEREAS, Dr. William Arnold is a TED Talk alumnus and highly respected national
speaker; he holds a bachelor's degree in sociology from the University of Tennessee and a
Master of Education degree in Administration and Supervision and an Ed.D. in higher education
administration from Tennessee State University; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Arnold epitomizes the spirit and commitment that are characteristic of a
true Tennessean; and
WHEREAS, it is most fitting that we acknowledge and applaud this esteemed
gentleman; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and commend Dr. William E. Arnold, Jr., for his remarkable
journey of resilience, advocacy, and leadership, extending our gratitude for his commitment to
advancing justice, equity, and opportunity for the citizens of this State.
